body:
[I have this code:](https://play.rust-lang.org/?gist=7f62c00d6734da5fa2d7ed3309a2fb84&version=stable&mode=debug)
````rust
macro_rules! typ {
    () => { i32 };
}

#[derive(Debug)]
struct MyStruct<T> {
    field: typ!(),
}
````

The compiler gives this error:
````
error: `derive` cannot be used on items with type macros
 --> src/main.rs:7:12
  |
7 |     field: typ!(),
  |            ^^^^^^
````

[But if I change MyStruct into non-generic type](https://play.rust-lang.org/?gist=12f89b224e155bc18ce0f090d23cc54e&version=stable&mode=debug)
````rust
macro_rules! typ {
    () => { i32 };
}

#[derive(Debug)]
struct MyStruct {
    field: typ!(),
}
````

It works without any error.

Why can't use #[derive] and macro on a generic type at the same time?
Is it a compiler bug?

[-> Mirror issue on StackOverflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/50296196/how-can-i-use-derive-on-a-type-containing-an-array-where-the-length-is-specif)
